":"after 1300","1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1258":"1258","Abt 1300":"about 1300","1235":"1235","1356":"1356","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","1306":"1306","Carnarvon Castle, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Carnarvon Castle, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Hanmer, Flintshire, Wales":"Hanmer, Flintshire, Wales","Hanmer, Wrexham, Wales":"Hanmer, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Macclesfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Maxfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maxfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from Macclesfield in Cheshire. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Maccel</i> (genitive <i>Macceles</i>) + Old English <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hanmer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: habitational name from Hanmer (Flintshire), named with the Old English personal name <i>Hagena</i> + Old English <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pond’. A daughter of Sir David <i>Hanmer</i>, a Welsh judge in the 14th century, was married to the Welsh ruler Owen Glendower, who led the revolt against Henry IV's rule in Wales.","English: habitational name from Anmer (Norfolk), from Old English <i>æned</i> ‘duck’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pond’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Upton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in England called Upton, most of which are named with Old English <i>upp</i> ‘upper’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different origins, such as one in Essex, originally named with the phrase <i>upp in tūne</i> ‘up in the settlement’, i.e. the higher part of the settlement, and Upton Lovell (Wiltshire), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ubba</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>. This name was brought to Ireland (Antrim) in 1598 by Henry <i>Upton</i>, from Upton in Devon."],"variants":[{"name":"Uptain","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Upton  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Upton Macclesfield de Hanmer was born in 1277, in Hanmer, Flintshire, Wales, his father, Earl Thomas de Macclesfield I, was 42 and his mother, Countess Millicent Hanmer, was 37. He had at least 3 sons with Hawise verch Einion. His occupation is listed as constable/knight of caernarvon castle in Caernarfonshire, Wales. He died in 1308, in Carnarvon Castle, Caernarfonshire, Wales, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1277–1308":"1277–1308","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1255–1300":"1255–1300","1258–1322":"1258–1322","1270–1356":"1270–1356","1284–1300":"1284–1300","1280–1300":"1280–1300","1300–1328":"1300–1328","–Male":"Surnud","1235–1310":"1235–1310","1240–1317":"1240–1317","aft 1300":"pärast 1300","1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1258":"1258","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1235":"1235","1356":"1356","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","1306":"1306","Carnarvon Castle, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Carnarvon Castle, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hanmer, Flintshire, Wales":"Hanmer, Flintshire, Wales","Hanmer, Wrexham, Wales":"Hanmer, Wrexham, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1277–1308":"1277–1308","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1255–1300":"1255–1300","1258–1322":"1258–1322","1270–1356":"1270–1356","1284–1300":"1284–1300","1280–1300":"1280–1300","1300–1328":"